                    <div class="panel panel-default">
                        <div class="panel-heading">
                            <h4 class="panel-title">
                                <a data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseThree">What services are available?
                                </a>
                            </h4>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapseThree" class="panel-collapse collapse">
                            <div class="panel-body">
                                <p>
                                    The Maryland LIDAR server has been created to provide open access to statewide elevation
                                    information for use in a variety of studies and applications.  The Maryland LIDAR server 
                                    maintains the best available elevation data and provides image services in both county 
                                    and statewide extents.
                                </p>
                                <strong>The Maryland LiDAR server supports multiple image services per county and statewide:</strong>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <i>Ground based digital elevation models (DEM) in feet and meters</i>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    A digital elevation model, or DEM is a raster representation of the earth’s 
                                                    surface created from LiDAR elevation data. The most common type of DEM is a 
                                                    bare earth DEM in which above ground objects like trees and buildings have 
                                                    been removed. DEMs are utilized for a variety of purposes including hydrology 
                                                    modeling, viewshed analysis, and line of sight analysis.  DEMs are also the 
                                                    first step in creating many other important derivative products such as slope, 
                                                    aspect, and hillshade.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <i>Color stretched visualization</i>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    Color stretched visualizations offer a more dynamic and traditional view of 
                                                    the DEMs by applying a color ramp to the elevation values.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <i>Slope</i>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    Slope identifies the inclination of the earth’s surface.  
                                                    The degree or percent of a slope is an important factor when analyzing slope stability, 
                                                    transportation, agriculture, recreation,etc.  Slope can be used alone or in conjunction 
                                                    with other layers for various site suitability analysis.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <i>Aspect</i>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    Aspect identifies slope direction in compass degrees where 0=north and 180=south.  
                                                    Aspect determines how much sunlight will strike the earth’s surface and therefore has 
                                                    important impacts on ecology, animal and vegetative habitats soil moisture, and many other 
                                                    biological and physical landscape characteristics.  It is also essential in many alternative 
                                                    energy project when considering site location of wind or solar facilities.
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <i>Hillshade</i>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>
                                                    Hillshade is used to determine the illumination of the earth’s surface.  
                                                    It can be used in analysis to understand the time and intensity of the sun at a given 
                                                    location or for graphical display purposes to enhance the relief of a surface.  
                                                </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
